01:31:46.260 --> 01:31:49.180
as it becomes in
Preti's painting.

01:31:49.180 --> 01:31:51.060
But yet, there is
that undercurrent

01:31:51.060 --> 01:31:53.540
of sexual tension
that's in the text.

01:31:53.540 --> 01:31:55.060
And you might want to
say more about that.

01:31:55.060 --> 01:31:57.380
&gt;&gt; Dr. Laura Benedetti:
Oh, absolutely, absolutely.

01:31:57.380 --> 01:32:01.700
There's this kind of
transformation of Clorinda

01:32:01.700 --> 01:32:09.000
in a completely different
female model, right?

01:32:09.000 --> 01:32:15.030
I mean, from the Titan and
warrior woman to the --

01:32:16.450 --> 01:32:19.670
[pause], you know,
Petrarchan ideal.

01:32:19.670 --> 01:32:25.070
In fact, the language really
mirrors Petrarca when she,

01:32:25.070 --> 01:32:30.470
in the crucial parts of the
dual and when she converts.

01:32:30.470 --> 01:32:34.120
So there is definitely an
erotization of Clorinda,

01:32:34.120 --> 01:32:39.040
who had, up to that moment,
completely neglected love.

01:32:39.040 --> 01:32:42.270
So it's absolutely there.

01:32:42.270 --> 01:32:45.790
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter Lukehart: I
was going to say though

01:32:45.790 --> 01:32:47.090
that you're linking

01:32:47.090 --> 01:32:52.850
in beautifully here both
the erotic scene of Sofronia

01:32:52.850 --> 01:32:58.660
and the very erotic scene of
Clorinda, as, you know, again,

01:32:59.830 --> 01:33:03.290
taking things from the
text and making a kind

01:33:03.290 --> 01:33:06.720
of poetic interpretation
on the basis of the artist.

01:33:17.510 --> 01:33:51.130
[ Inaudible Question ]

01:33:51.130 --> 01:33:52.430
&gt;&gt; Dr. Laura Benedetti:
Well, for Tasso,

01:33:52.430 --> 01:33:57.440
and this is already a pretext
from Francesco DeSantis

01:33:57.440 --> 01:34:02.490
that pointed out in Tasso there
are two different worlds really,

01:34:02.490 --> 01:34:05.100
what it says that
it wants to do,

01:34:05.100 --> 01:34:07.610
and what he actually
ends up doing.

01:34:07.610 --> 01:34:11.310
So in his letters,
it's very clear.

01:34:11.310 --> 01:34:14.090
He says, in my poem,
love is the instrument

01:34:14.090 --> 01:34:19.080
to [inaudible] the
audience, the devil's tool.

01:34:19.080 --> 01:34:24.470
So love is there only to
be destroyed, essentially.

01:34:24.470 --> 01:34:27.950
Only to be defeated
at the end, right?

01:34:27.950 --> 01:34:34.060
And in one of the first
stanzas, he says that basically,

01:34:34.060 --> 01:34:39.210
it's poetry and love and
only the sugar coating

01:34:39.210 --> 01:34:44.890
for the bitter medicine that
the reader is going to swallow.

01:34:44.890 --> 01:34:47.630
[laughter] So essentially,
he has a moral message

01:34:47.630 --> 01:34:50.230
and love is supposed to
make it more agreeable.

01:34:50.230 --> 01:34:53.240
But at the end, what
matters is the message.

01:34:53.240 --> 01:34:56.100
That's what he says
he intends to do.

01:34:56.100 --> 01:35:01.360
But then, as we have
seen in these characters,

01:35:01.360 --> 01:35:04.290
he's very convincing
when he talks about love

01:35:04.290 --> 01:35:07.940
and these characters seem
to take a life of their own.

01:35:07.940 --> 01:35:12.930
And so when he tried to, in a
way, to really limit all of that

01:35:12.930 --> 01:35:15.310
and come out with the
"Gerusalemme conquistata,"

01:35:15.310 --> 01:35:19.700
the public didn't follow that.

01:35:19.700 --> 01:35:27.010
So I -- he seems to be
championing a different,

01:35:27.010 --> 01:35:28.550
more modern way of love.

01:35:28.550 --> 01:35:34.320
Luckily for us, he actually
succeeded in expressing some

01:35:34.320 --> 01:35:37.250
of the most beautiful
love stories

01:35:37.250 --> 01:35:41.200
that have ever been written.

